    "markdown": "## Pregnancy TIFFA Scan for Twins – Level 2 Ultrasound at Cadabams Diagnostics\n\nExpecting twins is twice the joy—and twice the need for precision imaging. The \\*\\*Pregnancy TIFFA Scan – Twins Level 2 Ultrasound Scan\\*\\* offered at Cadabams Diagnostics is specifically designed to give your babies a detailed head-to-toe check-up while keeping you informed, reassured, and prepared.\n## What Is the Pregnancy TIFFA Scan – Twins Level 2 Ultrasound Scan?\n### Definition and Medical Terminology\n- \\*\\*TIFFA\\*\\* stands for \\*\\*Targeted Imaging for Fetal Anomalies\\*\\*.\n- It is a \\*\\*Level 2 ultrasound\\*\\*, which means it uses advanced transducers and software to capture high-resolution images beyond routine dating scans.\n### Why Twins Need Specialized Imaging\n- Two babies mean two sets of organs to examine in the same session.\n- Each twin may lie in a different plane, requiring real-time adjustments by our experienced sonographers.\n- Early detection of \\*\\*Twin-to-Twin Transfusion Syndrome (TTTS)\\*\\* or \\*\\*selective fetal growth restriction\\*\\* can be lifesaving.\nKey difference: Unlike a quick heartbeat confirmation scan, the TIFFA scan spends 30–45 minutes systematically evaluating every organ system in both babies.\n## Types of Pregnancy TIFFA Scans Available at Cadabams Diagnostics\n- \\*\\*Transabdominal 2D/3D/4D ultrasound\\*\\* – primary imaging mode.\n- \\*\\*Doppler assessment\\*\\* – checks blood flow between twins to rule out TTTS.\n- \\*\\*Fetal echocardiography add-on\\*\\* – detailed heart scan when requested.\n\n## When and Who Needs This Scan?\n\n### Ideal Gestational Age Window\n- \\*\\*18–22 weeks\\*\\* is the sweet spot: organs are large enough to see, yet amniotic fluid still provides good acoustic windows.\n### Indications\n- All \\*\\*twin pregnancies\\*\\* regardless of risk level.\n- Maternal age \\*\\*>30 years\\*\\*.\n- Family history of congenital anomalies.\n- Obstetrician referral after abnormal first-trimester screening.\n\n## Risks & Limitations\n\n| Aspect | Details |\n|--------|---------|\n| \\*\\*Safety\\*\\* | Ultrasound uses sound waves; \\*\\*no radiation risk\\*\\*. |\n| \\*\\*Accuracy\\*\\* | Up to 95 % of major anomalies can be detected. |\n| \\*\\*Missed Anomalies\\*\\* | Subtle heart defects or cleft palate can occasionally be missed. |\n| \\*\\*Technical Limits\\*\\* | Maternal obesity or fetal position may obscure some views. |\n> Tip: If one twin is lying face-down, our radiologist may ask you to gently shift position or schedule a short follow-up.\n\n## Parameters Evaluated During the Scan\n\n### Anatomical Checklist\n- \\*\\*Brain\\*\\* – ventricles, cerebellum, midline structures\n- \\*\\*Spine\\*\\* – neural tube closure\n- \\*\\*Heart\\*\\* – four chambers, outflow tracts, septa\n- \\*\\*Kidneys\\*\\* – size, echogenicity, pelvis dilation\n- \\*\\*Limbs\\*\\* – long bones, digits\n- \\*\\*Face\\*\\* – lips, palate profile\n- \\*\\*Diaphragm\\*\\* – integrity and movement\n### Biometric Measurements\n| Parameter | Twin A | Twin B |\n|-----------|--------|--------|\n| \\*\\*CRL / BPD\\*\\* | Crown-rump length or biparietal diameter | Same |\n| \\*\\*HC\\*\\* | Head circumference | Same |\n| \\*\\*AC\\*\\* | Abdominal circumference | Same |\n| \\*\\*FL\\*\\* | Femur length | Same |\n### Additional Checks\n- \\*\\*Placental localization\\*\\* – placenta previa, velamentous cord\n- \\*\\*Amniotic fluid index\\*\\* – polyhydramnios / oligohydramnios\n- \\*\\*Cervical length\\*\\* – risk of preterm labor\n- \\*\\*Umbilical and middle cerebral artery Doppler flows\\*\\*\n\n## Key Reasons to Take the Scan\n\n- \\*\\*Detect structural birth defects early\\*\\* to plan surgery or delivery route.\n- \\*\\*Monitor twin growth discordance\\*\\* (>20 % difference raises red flags).\n- \\*\\*Rule out soft markers\\*\\* for chromosomal anomalies (e.g., echogenic bowel).\n\n## Benefits for Expectant Parents\n\n- \\*\\*Early intervention planning\\*\\* – transfer to tertiary center if needed.\n- \\*\\*Reassurance\\*\\* – 90 % of scans show normal findings.\n- \\*\\*Delivery guidance\\*\\* – vaginal vs. cesarean based on placental site and fetal positions.\n\n## Illnesses Diagnosed\n\n| Condition | Description |\n|-----------|-------------|\n| \\*\\*Neural tube defects\\*\\* | Spina bifida, anencephaly |\n| \\*\\*Congenital heart disease\\*\\* | VSD, ASD, Tetralogy of Fallot |\n| \\*\\*Facial anomalies\\*\\* | Cleft lip/palate |\n| \\*\\*Limb deformities\\*\\* | Clubfoot, missing digits |\n| \\*\\*Twin-to-Twin Transfusion Syndrome\\*\\* | Unequal blood sharing across shared placenta |\n\n## How to Prepare\n\n- \\*\\*Hydration\\*\\*: Drink \\*\\*500 ml water 30 min prior\\*\\* unless told otherwise; a full bladder lifts the uterus for clearer images.\n- \\*\\*Clothing\\*\\*: Wear a \\*\\*loose two-piece outfit\\*\\* for easy access to abdomen.\n- \\*\\*Reports\\*\\*: Bring earlier scan printouts and recent blood test results.\n## Pre-requisites\n- Valid doctor prescription.\n- Completed maternal history form.\n- Insurance pre-authorization (our front desk can help).\n## Best Time to Book\n- Schedule between \\*\\*18–22 weeks\\*\\*.\n- Book early in pregnancy; twin scan slots fill fast.\n- Follow-up scan at 26–28 weeks if initial views were suboptimal.\n## Eligibility\n- \\*\\*All twin pregnancies\\*\\* automatically qualify.\n- \\*\\*Singleton pregnancies\\*\\* with risk factors may also opt for TIFFA.\n## Step-by-Step Procedure at Cadabams Diagnostics\n1. \\*\\*Check-in\\*\\* – ID verification ensures correct patient data.\n2. \\*\\*Gel application\\*\\* – warm, hypoallergenic gel is used.\n3. \\*\\*Imaging Twin A\\*\\* – systematic sweep from head to toe.\n4. \\*\\*Imaging Twin B\\*\\* – same protocol, adjusting probe angle.\n5. \\*\\*Real-time discussion\\*\\* – radiologist explains findings on screen.\n6. \\*\\*Report\\*\\* – color printouts handed over same day; soft copy emailed within 2 hours.\n## Cautions Before the Test\n- Inform staff of \\*\\*latex allergy\\*\\* for probe cover alternatives.\n- Report \\*\\*vaginal bleeding or pain\\*\\* immediately.\n- \\*\\*Skip caffeine\\*\\* 2 hours prior to reduce excessive fetal movement."
  },
